messages.content:
Creating an NFT minting application that works in a single HTML file with embedded CSS and JS is a bit limited because minting NFTs typically requires interaction with a blockchain, which should be done through a wallet or smart contract on the Ethereum network or similar platforms. Below is a simplified example of how you can create an HTML template that simulates minting an NFT each time the page loads. 

This example does not interact with a real blockchain but demonstrates the basic concept of generating and displaying an NFT-like digital art image using JavaScript and CSS.

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
    <title>NFT Minting Simulation</title>
    <style>
        body {
            font-family: Arial, sans-serif;
            display: flex;
            justify-content: center;
            align-items: center;
            flex-direction: column;
            height: 100vh;
            background-color: #f0f0f0;
            margin: 0;
        }
        .nft-container {
            border: 2px solid #333;
            border-radius: 10px;
            padding: 20px;
            background-color: #fff;
            box-shadow: 0 4px 8px rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.2);
            text-align: center;
        }
        img {
            max-width: 100%;
            border-radius: 10px;
        }
        button {
            margin-top: 20px;
            padding: 10px 20px;
            font-size: 16px;
            background-color: #007BFF;
            color: white;
            border: none;
            border-radius: 5px;
            cursor: pointer;
        }
        button:hover {
            background-color: #0056b3;
        }
    </style>
</head>
<body>
    <div class="nft-container">
        <h1>Your NFT</h1>
        <img id="nftImage" src="" alt="NFT Art">
        <p id="nftDescription"></p>
        <button onclick="generateNFT()">Mint New NFT</button>
    </div>

    <script>
        const nftImages = [
            'https://i.imgur.com/tWZR3jA.png',
            'https://i.imgur.com/4VZs2Xj.png',
            'https://i.imgur.com/Rvu1qUx.png',
            'https://i.imgur.com/09Hqp0X.png'
        ];

        const nftDescriptions = [
            'A beautiful sunset over the mountains.',
            'An abstract representation of energy and creativity.',
            'A futuristic cityscape at night.',
            'A serene lake surrounded by forest.'
        ];

        function getRandomInt(max) {
            return Math.floor(Math.random() * max);
        }

        function generateNFT() {
            const index = getRandomInt(nftImages.length);
            const nftImage = document.getElementById('nftImage');
            const nftDescription = document.getElementById('nftDescription');
            nftImage.src = nftImages[index];
            nftDescription.innerText = nftDescriptions[index];
        }

        // Mint an NFT on page load
        window.onload = generateNFT;
    </script>
</body>
</html>
```

### Explanation
- **HTML Structure**: The page has a container for displaying the NFT image and its description, along with a button to mint a new NFT.
- **CSS Styling**: Basic styling is provided to center the content and give it a clean look.
- **JavaScript Logic**:
  - We define a few sample images and descriptions to simulate NFTs.
  - A function `getRandomInt` is used to generate a random index to select an image and description.
  - The `generateNFT` function is called on page load to display an NFT and can also be triggered by the button click.

### Note
This example does not implement actual NFT minting on a blockchain. For real-world applications, you would interact with smart contracts via a library such as Web3.js or ethers.js, use MetaMask or similar wallets, and connect to a blockchain such as Ethereum.
